data.shownotes:
This show featured the debut of Sense. Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before and as the band came on stage. Only Part I of The River was performed. Wah Wah contained The River quotes and teases. Work This Time contained a false start due to the band starting at the wrong tempo and featured a guitar solo.

Poster By Jason Galea
Edition of 100

data.jamchart_notes: Following Cyboogie and Acarine, this version starts pretty normal and they let it ride as they tend to do, but then the vocoder comes back out. Sounds like Cyboogie and Sense had a baby.
data.shownotes:
Evil Star was played through the PA speakers as the band came on stage. Sense featured use of a Vocoder during part of the vocals. Before Head On/Pill, the Han-Tyumi voice was used to say "Hello" repeatedly, as well as "Thank you", as the band thanked the crowd and opening acts ORB and Stonefield. Head On/Pill contained Am I In Heaven?, People-Vultures, Alter Me, and Boogieman Sam teases and quotes, and Cyboogie, Robot Stop, I'm In Your Mind, Rattlesnake, and Hot Water teases.

Poster By Jason Galea
Edition of 100

Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before the band as came on stage. Mr. Beat was played for the first time since 2016-09-22. (215 show gap) The Han-Tyumi voice said "Thank You" after Evil Death Roll, after Murder of the Universe, and after Altered Beast II. Only one verse of Alter Me I was sung. Mars For the Rich is included in the Chunky Shrapnel Special Features.

Poster By Jason Galea
Edition of 200

data.jamchart_notes: Guitar-focused but with a steady drumbeat anchor, accented with Amby's floaty synth work in particular. Joey in fine form, leading mostly. Not yet the full band improv of 2023 Senses
data.shownotes: The River contained Wah Wah teases and quotes. Am I in Heaven? contained Cellophane and Cyboogie teases, and a Head on Pill jam. Venusian 2 through Sense was released through the Official Bootlegger program as part of Live in Brussels ‘19. Cavs’s drum solo during ‘Open Water’ is featured in the ‘Chunky Shrapnel’ album under the name 'Parking'. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. All songs besides Doom City have been confirmed via audio/video recordings, and The River is incomplete. Doom City has been confirmed through contemporaneous discussions through various social media. Any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net. Poster By Jason Galea Edition of 400

This show featured the debut of Dirt. After Doom City, the band said happy birthday to Joey. The Bitter Boogie contained elements of Back Door Man (Howlin' Wolf) as well as Cut Throat Boogie and On The Road Again (Canned Heat) quotes. Gamma Knife featured a Robot Stop tease. During The Bitter Boogie, Ambrose went crowdsurfing. Portions of Sense featured in 'Chunky Shrapnel' film.

Poster By Jason Galea
Edition of 200

Evil Star was played through the PA speakers as the band went on stage. Cut Throat Boogie contained a Cruel Millennial outro. Wah Wah contained a River intro as well as The River teases and quotes. During the River intro of Wah Wah an audience member got on stage, who Joey then passed his microphone to before security escorted them offstage. Am I In Heaven? contained Robot Stop, Head On/Pill, Cellophane and I'm In Your Mind quotes and teases, Boogieman Sam and Hot Wax quotes and Hot Water teases, as well as featuring Stu on vocoder and later flute for an extended Hot Water jam which was followed by Cavs crowd surfing while Stu played drums. Let Me Mend the Past and Wah Wah from this show are featured in the Chunky Shrapnel album.

Poster By Jason Galea
Edition of 100

KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. The Great Chain of Being and Sense through Murder Of The Universe were confirmed through audio/video recording. The remaining songs were confirmed via contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.

This was the first 3 hour marathon-like concert, performed for fundraising and awareness of recent Australian bushfires, and the last concert performed with drummer Eric Moore. Evil Star intro song played from house speakers before the show. I'm Not in Your Mind contained a Cellophane tease. Cellophane contained Alter Me teases and quotes. Wah Wah contained The River teases and quotes. Willoughby's Beach was played for the first time known since 2016-06-25. (280 shows) Sea of Trees was played for the first time since 2017-04-02 (214 shows) and contained Head On/Pill teases. Work This Time contained a guitar solo. Superbug was dedicated to the Coronavirus.

This show was a fully acoustic warmup gig for acoustic night of the Princess Theatre residency and featured the debut of Most of What I Like. It's Got Old was played for the first time since 2015-09-13. (354 show gap) Sleepwalker was played for the first time since 2016-02-28. (325 show gap) Most Of What I Like contained “Praise You” (Fatboy Slim) teases. The intro to Sense contained “Come On” (The Notorious B.I.G.) quotes. Prior to Slow Jam 1 opening band The Bush was shouted out and mention was made that Ambrose's sister Edith is in the band. The song itself contained a Her and I (Slow Jam 2) tease.

This was the Acoustic Night show of the Princess Theatre residency, the first of five planned shows, each featuring a different specific genre and preannounced songs. The Bitter Boogie was dedicated to “the last two years.” Most Of What I Like contained Praise You (Fatboy Slim) teases. Her and I contained Slow Jam 1 quotes. This show was released through the Official Bootlegger program as Live in Brisbane '21. Poster By Jason Galea Edition of 200

data.jamchart_notes: Super chill funky version starting off with a drum machine jam by Joey and ending in a guitar solo.
data.shownotes:
Cavs was unable to play due to getting COVID before the show. The band played with a drum machine with a Cavs shirt draped on top. Joey mentioned they would have gotten a fan on the drums if not for COVID restrictions. Sense opened with Joey doing jamming on the drum machine for a few minutes before the band came on and began playing Sense. Let Me Mend The Past featured Joey on acoustic guitar. Sleepwalker, Mystery Jack, and Presumptuous featured Cookie on acoustic guitar. Work This Time featured a guitar solo. Sea of Trees contained a Head On/Pill tease and a Change tease. 

Poster By B.Montero
data.soundcheck: Let Me Mend The Past, Rattlesnake, Hot Water, and Work This Time

data.shownotes: Gaia contained Motor Spirit teases. Slow Jam I contained Iron Lung teases. Opening acts The Prize and CLAMM were shouted out after Sense. Shanghai was introduced as being about a fight the band got into in Shanghai. Lava, Gamma Knife and People-Vultures were on the written setlist as the final three songs but were not played. Poster by Troppo Print Studio 200 Standard / 20 Foil Print

Let Me Mend The Past contained an It Ain't Me, Babe (Bob Dylan) quote. Sense was teased immediately before and during Ice V, which contained a Hypertension tease. Ambergris was introduced as “Joey’s porno song”. The Dripping Tap contained Hot Water teases and quotes with the lyrics changed to “time to party” and “everybody wants to party”, and Cellophane teases. Boogieman Sam contained “Going Up the Country” (Canned Heat), “Got My Mojo Working” (Ann Cole), “My Babe” (Little Walter) and “It's a Long Way to the Top (If You Wanna Rock 'N' Roll)” (AC/DC) quotes and Am I In Heaven? teases. Float Along – Fill Your Lungs contained a metal jam. Poster By Lewy Jones

data.jamchart_notes: This 12 minute long version is played electric, instead of the acoustic version. It features a slowed down version of Iron Lung and a mashup of Straws in the Wind and Sense lyrics.
data.shownotes: This show featured the debuts of Motor Spirit and Hate Dancin’. Gaia featured a drum solo by Cavs. Motor Spirit was incomplete. Sense contained Am I In Heaven? teases, Iron Lung quotes, Head On/Pill teases, and a Straws in the Wind vocal jam with “no sense at all” vocals. The Grim Reaper featured “I’m the Shrimp Reaper” vocals and contained Torture Chamber quotes. Following Astroturf, Cavs’ parents briefly appeared on stage. Down the Sink was played for the first time since May 24, 2022 (70 show gap) and had lyrics changed to “the street is where people jam.” Robot Stop contained Hot Water and The Dripping Tap teases and quotes, an Extinction quote, and a proto-Grow Wings and Fly jam. Gamma Knife contained Motor Spirit teases. Iron Lung contained Sense teases. Poster By Jason Galea 1200 Standard / 300 Foil Prints

Stu and Joey wore overalls, which were also worn in the video for The Silver Cord. I’m Not In Your Mind contained Alter Me quotes and The Dripping Tap teases/quotes. Sense contained a Slow Jam 1 intro, after which Stu introduced Joey as John Frusciante and the band played a brief Red Hot Chili Peppers style jam. Sense proper contained Slow Jam 1 quotes and closed with quotes of “Incredible” (M Beat) and “Welcome to the Jungle” (Guns N’ Roses). The Grim Reaper contained Torture Chamber quotes and “Intergalactic” (Beastie Boys) quotes. Shanghai featured the “grow wings and fly” jam. Ambergris was introduced as a song about Free Willy. Hot Water had lyrics changed to “Joe Walker" and "Joey Walker." Robot Stop was unfinished and contained Hot Water teases, The Dripping Tap teases and Witchcraft teases/quotes. Lava and Gamma Knife were on the printed setlist but were not played. At the end of the show, the band thanked the crowd for coming to see the "fishermen from Australia". KGLW.net Staff Notes: There was much internal discussion as to a potential tease of the intro to Gondii in Change. The arrangement of instruments and structure of Change has been modified compared with the studio version. Though it resembles a tease of Gondii, we believe more live instances need to he heard to determine if this is intentional, or just an accentuation of the existing relationship between the songs. Poster By Jason Galea 420 Standard / 120 Foil

Grace Cummings returned from illness as the opening act. Float Along - Fill Your Lungs contained a Dragon jam with lyrics. Boogieman Sam contained a Sad Pilot jam with lyrics, "Midnight Rambler" (The Rolling Stones) quotes, and “Boogie” (Carson) teases and quotes. The Dripping Tap was dedicated to "everyone with diarrhea" and contained a You Can Be Your Sillouhette jam and Mycelium quotes. The Wheel was dedicated to David, the band's bus driver. This Thing contained an “Incredible” (M Beat) quote. Self-Immolate contained a drum solo. Following Converge, Joey shouted out opener Grace Cummings. Witchcraft was on the printed setlist after Converge, but was skipped. Poster by Amy Jean; Edition of 100

This show featured the (incomplete) debut of Mirage City, and the debuts of Time = $$$ and You Can Be Your Silhouette. Iron Lung contained Witchcraft teases. Most Of What I Like contained Praise You (Fatboy Slim) teases. Time = $$$ was introduced as “Stairway to Heaven” (Led Zeppelin), which was then teased. You Can Be Your Silhouette contained an Iron Lung tease. The Bitter Boogie contained the drum pattern from Muddy Water and a lyric change to "shits his pants". Hot Water contained a Cellophane tease. Following Hot Water, Joey noted that the band has a microtonal acoustic guitar, but only one, and jokingly suggested that Stu should play Rattlesnake solo, who then sang it along with teases of it from Joey and Ambrose. Soon after, Stu teased “Hey Joe” (Jimi Hendrix) which led to Joey remarking he used to get made fun of for playing it in school. Following Trapdoor, Joey called Cavs down to ask him when he played drums, to which he replied around 16. Ambrose then quoted Pleura. Sad Pilot was introduced as a song about being sad. Following Sad Pilot, Stu quoted Rattlesnake again. Sense contained You Can Be Your Sillouhette teases and a Witchcraft tease. This Thing contained an "Incredible" (M Beat) quote. The intro to Slow Jam 1 contained a The River tease and the song itself contained Ice V teases. Before Witchcraft, Stu told a story about a fan giving him a CD of acoustic songs from PetroDragonic Apocalypse and that inspired the band to play Witchcraft acoustic. Poster by Amy Jean; Edition of 100

The intro to O.N.E. contained a Straws in The Wind tease. The Book was played for the first time since 2023-03-07	(82 show gap). Gaia contained a You Can Be Your Sillhouette tease and featured a drum solo. Plastic Boogie was played for the first time since 2023-06-13 (55 show gap). This Thing contained The Dripping Tap teases and a Hell's Itch tease. Slow Jam 1 and Sense featured Ambrose on sax. Before Field of Vision, the band pretended like they were going to play Hog Calling Contest but they did a jam loosely based on it with lyrics based on the movie The Mask. Big Fig Wasp contained the ending of Robot Stop as the intro. The intro to People-Vultures and the song itself contained Iron Lung jams with lyrics. Iron Lung contained a People-Vultures jam with lyrics.

Poster by Jason Galea
Standard Edition - 600
Foil Edition - 150

Chang'e contained Witchcraft quotes from the extended mix. Sense contained Witchcraft teases. Following Raw Feel, Cavs teased Hey Pachuco (Royal Crown Revue) from The Mask. Ambrose teased Flight b741 before Dirt. Following Dirt, Ambrose called Joey "Joe Dirt". Following Flight b741, Joey asked the crowd if anyone in the band had been to their 2022 show in San Diego (2022-04-11) and Stu asked if anyone had been to The Soda Bar (2016-05-18 and 2015-08-25), mentioning there was someone dressed in a panda suit there, who he then spotted in the crowd. Iron Lung contained Can't Stop (Red Hot Chili Peppers) and Witchcraft teases. Muddy Water contained The Bitter Boogie and The Castle In The Air teases. The Bitter Boogie contained the drums from Muddy Water as well as teases. After The Bitter Boogie, Joey teased Good Riddance (Green Day) and Every Morning (Sugar Ray) and asked Sammy to turn his mic through the PA, and Joey teased Every Morning and Good Riddance again. Ambrose then jokingly brought up Green Day’s infamous 2012 iHeartRadio incident (during which the band destroyed their instruments angrily after being told their set was being cut short) and multiple band members quoted Billie Joe Armstrong’s exclamations from the performance. God Is Calling Me Back Home had lyrics changed to "She's calling me back home" and featured Joey playing guitar with a beer bottle. Inbetween God Is Calling Me Back Home and Magma, Joey teased Tell Me Why (Neil Young). Magma was played for Sammy, featured an extended intro where the band shouted out their crew members, did not have the "rumble" verse, and contained a The Silver Cord jam with lyrics. After Magma, the band jokingly played a portion of Gaia acoustically. Theia contained Motor Spirit teases & quotes and The River teases. Only Part I of The River (which was introduced as a song about "when you wake up in the morning, and you smell something, in the kitchen, it’s not supposed to be there, and it smells real good, and you go eat it, and then you feel real good, then you feel real sick") was performed and it contained Motor Spirit teases, Theia teases, and a The Silver Cord vocal jam with Theia quotes. Honey and Pleura were on some of the written setlists following Horology but were replaced with Magma.
data.venuename: The Rady Shell at Jacobs Park

data.shownotes: This show featured the debut of Smoke & Mirrors. The Dripping Tap contained a Chang'e and Head On/Pill tease and an Antarctica vocal tease. Before Flight b741, the band talked about the clouds at the venue, and Joey quoted Field of Vision, and Stu referenced The Land Before Time. Intrasport was played without the synth table. Sense was played in an alternate synth version for the first time. During Grim Reaper, which contained "Black Market Bargain" lyrics and Get Low (Lil Jon) and H.O.O.D. (Kneecap) quotes. Amby called out, "are you not entertained?" in reference to Gladiator. Only Ambrose's verses of Smoke & Mirrors were performed, and the song contained The Grim Reaper teases. Gaia and Gila Monster ended in a drum solos. Before Inner Cell, Stu teased Loyalty.

Oddlife was introduced as Cookie's favorite song. Sense was performed in it's synth arrangement and contained The Grim Reaper teases. The Grim Reaper contained Intergalactic, Sabotage, and (You Gotta) Fight for Your Right (To Party!) (all by the Beastie Boys) quotes, and at the end of the song Ambrose thanked the Beastie Boys. Wah Wah contained a The River intro with Crumbling Castle teases and the song itself contained The River quotes, Crumbling Castle teases and Extinction teases and quotes. Let Me Mend The Past, which contained an It Ain't Me, Babe (Bob Dylan) quote, was dedicated to Amby's hangover anxieties. Hypertension contained Extinction teases and quotes. Alter Me (unnumbered) was on the setlist before Altered Beast IV but was not played.

The band dressed in drag for the third annual drag night. Theia, Sad Pilot, Most Of What I Like, and Aerodynamic were performed acoustic. Theia contained The River and The Land Before Timeland teases. Most Of What I Like contained Praise You (Fatboy Slim) teases and was dedicated by Joey to his wife Edith. Aerodynamic was played for the first time without an orchestra. Before Venusian 1, the band said if they should have soundchecked it and joked that if they messed it up, they would play Stoned Mullet instead. Following Venusian 1, Joey quoted Chop Suey (System of a Down) and Lucas shouted out festival act Yvie Oddly. Her and I (Slow Jam 2) contained You Can Be Your Silhouette, Am I In Heaven?, The River, Blindness (The Fall), Crumbling Castle, and Monkey Disco (Babe Rainbow) teases. Following Her and I, the band announced that the festival would be played again next year, and shouted out their manager Michelle Cable and the fans at the festival. O.N.E. was introduced as Duran Duran's favorite song. Before Billabong Valley, Joey mentioned Australian rapper RAED. During The Silver Cord, Stu vamped on the lyrics "let's get fucked up" and "everybody wants to save us." Following Daily Blues, Ambrose quoted Scarface (Push It to the Limit) (Paul Engemann). Float Along - Fill Your Lungs was dedicated to Matt Gawiak, a fan that passed away during the show night 1 of the festival and contained a Dragon jam. Ambrose led the crowd in a chant of 'Matt' following Float Along - Fill Your Lungs. The Dripping Tap was also dedicated to Matt Gawaik. Rats In The sky was on the printed setlist after The Garden Goblin but was skipped.

This show featured the debut of Dreams. 2.02 Killer Year contained Shanghai teases. Shanghai contained Grow Wings and Fly teases and quotes, as well as the "let's get real high" refrain. Kepler-22b had it's lyrics changed to "dancin' is good for ya". At the end of the show, Joey said Free Palestine. The Silver Cord was on the printed setlist as the final song but was skipped for time.

Theia contained a Gilgamesh quote and The Silver Cord lyrics from Theia's extended mix. Shanghai contained a Grow Wings and Fly jam with lyrics. The Grim Reaper featured Ambrose performing the first two verses in the mosh pit, had a lyric changed to "the Grim Reaper cashes the Czech Republic" and contained Sabotage (Beastie Boys) (with lyrics changed to "listen all of Prague it's a sabotage"), Intergalatic (Beastie Boys), Bonkers (Dizzee Rascal), Torture Chamber, and Rollin' (Air Raid Vehicle) (Limp Bizkit) quotes. Ice V contained Superposition and Blindness (The Fall) teases. Candles contained a Superposition tease. Sense and Flamethrower (Outro) were swapped on the printed setlist.
